\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Create Folder (F7)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Description: 
\emph default
A quick way to create a folder group with as many tracks as you need.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Notes: 
\emph default
Use on a completely empty project.
 I would use this if you are planning to use a horizontal approach to source-des
tination editing (i.e.
 the various takes are laid out from left to right) or if you want a quick
 way to set up a mixing/mastering track set with a single take.
 The script automatically sets up the tracks for group media and razor-editing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Create Source Groups (vertical) (F8)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Description: 
\emph default
A multi-use script to 1) set up destination and source groups with as many
 tracks as you need, 2) to create source groups from an existing destination
 folder group (for example, created with F7 shortcut) and, for in the middle
 of editing, 3) to (re)create track grouping and to sync routing/fx between
 destination (the top folder and its children) and source groups.
 Note that for 3), all folders must contain the same number of tracks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Notes: 
\emph default
Whether you start with an empty project or use an existing folder group
 or groups, the end result will be the same.
 Folders and tracks will be grouped according to pan, mute, editing, phase,
 trim and fader.
 So, for example, the second track of each group will all respond to a fader
 movement.
 This is essential for being able to audition different source groups with
 the same settings.
 Note also that running the script engages an intelligent mixer view where
 only the soloed group is shown in the mixer.
 You can see this in action by using the Audition (A) script which auditions
 audio at the mouse cursor.
 Watch as the mixer view changes which tracks are visible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Explode multi-channel item (F10)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Description:
\emph default
 Explode multi-channel item(s) to either all mono or stereo-interleaved
 + mono
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Notes:
\emph default
 First create a folder (F7) or multiple folders (F8) and import the multi-channe
l item(s) onto the same folder track (important!).
 Select one or more items of the same channel count.
 Run the script and then choose 
\begin_inset Quotes bld
\end_inset

yes
\begin_inset Quotes brd
\end_inset

 to convert the first two iso tracks to stereo or 
\begin_inset Quotes bld
\end_inset

no
\begin_inset Quotes brd
\end_inset

 to leave as mono.
 Depending on the choice, the number of tracks in the folder will be increased
 or decreased with the all-mono option leaving the folder track itself empty
 ready to run prepare takes (T) to create a muted guide track.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Add Aux/Submix track to end of tracklist (@)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Description: 
\emph default
Add a green (#4c9165) aux/submix track prefixed with an ampersand (@) to
 the end of the tracklist but is only visible in the mixer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Notes: 
\emph default
This allows the user to keep assigned aux/submix tracks visible in the intellige
nt mixer.
 Create any connections to the aux/submix in the destination group (including
 child tracks) and then push to the source groups via the 
\emph on
Create Source Groups
\emph default
 script (F8).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Hide and Show child tracks (D and E)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Description: 
\emph default
Hide child tracks to save screen estate and for working with multi-channel
 takes as if working with just stereo.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Notes: 
\emph default
Select a folder track and press D to hide the children or E to show them.
 All S-D and razor editing functions work perfectly while folder groups
 are collapsed.
 This recreates a popular way of working with classical music takes in Pyramix.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Classical Take Record (F9)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Description:
\emph default
 A one-button shortcut for stopping and starting recording of takes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Notes:
\emph default
 To use, highlight a folder, position the edit cursor and press F9.
 Press again to stop the recording.
 To immediately start a new take, simply press F9 again.
 Note that the next folder is selected and that the cursor returns to the
 original position for easy lining up of takes.
 If you run out of source groups, the script will automatically create a
 new one.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Prepare Takes (T)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Description:
\emph default
 Intelligently prepares recorded or imported takes for source-destination
 editing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Notes: 
\emph default
With a single folder group (or individual tracks), the shortcut will auto-color
 and group takes from left to right.
 With a vertical workflow consisting of a destination group and multiple
 source groups, the script will auto-color top to bottom and group folder
 items left to right.
 Essentially in either setup, takes are given different colors and all items
 associated with a take grouped for editing.
 If you don't like the colors, run the script again until you are happy!
 The script also allows for takes that don't start or end exactly at the
 same time (this can happen if you receive pre-edited materials).
 The end result is if you drag one item of a take group, every other item
 will move in sync.
 NOTE: After you have started making S-D edits, the script will no longer
 offer to group or colour items due to potentially unexpected editing behaviour.
 The script was designed for use after initial recording or importing of
 media only.
 It will still offer to delete any existing take names after a user-friendly
 message.
 A reminder that the new REAPER native grouping (when set up via Create
 Folder or Create Source Groups sripts) works for 99% of situations without
 Prepare Takes but for takes that don't start or end at quite the same point
 it is a must.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Duplicate Folder (no items) (
\backslash
)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Description: 
\emph default
Create a duplicate without media items of the highlighted folder.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Notes: 
\emph default
Now that Classical Take Record (F9) automatically creates new folders if
 needed, this script does not need to be used when recording material.
 However, if importing pre-recorded takes and you need more source groups
 to accommodate the material, this is still very useful.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Colorize (K)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Description: 
\emph default
Add a identifying custom color to an item and those in the same group.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
